WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:10.000
Our first speaker is Neal Richardson from Ursa Labs.

00:00:10.000 --> 00:00:11.000
Thanks.

00:00:11.000 --> 00:00:12.000
All right.

00:00:12.000 --> 00:00:28.520
So I'm going to talk today about the Arrow project, both the Arrow R package, as well

00:00:28.520 --> 00:00:31.760
as the broader Apache Arrow project that it's within.

00:00:31.760 --> 00:00:36.959
I've got a link to the slides there, and I've also tweeted it at NPR.

00:00:36.959 --> 00:00:42.639
You can also tweet at us or follow us at Apache Arrow for more news.

00:00:42.639 --> 00:00:44.520
Don't worry if you don't copy this down.

00:00:44.520 --> 00:00:49.000
I've got a link to the slide on every slide, a link to the slides on every slide.

00:00:49.000 --> 00:00:56.799
So before I jump in to talk about Arrow, I first wanted to introduce who I am and who

00:00:56.799 --> 00:00:58.520
Ursa Labs is.

00:00:58.520 --> 00:01:02.720
I'm the maintainer of the R package for Arrow, and I'm also the engineering director with

00:01:02.720 --> 00:01:03.720
Ursa Labs.

00:01:03.720 --> 00:01:12.320
And we are a nonprofit that is oriented at funding open data tools, we're sponsored by

00:01:12.320 --> 00:01:20.699
RStudio and a number of other companies, and we are focused on the Apache Arrow ecosystem.

00:01:20.699 --> 00:01:24.760
If you're interested in learning more about us or have follow-up questions from the talk,

00:01:24.760 --> 00:01:32.360
we're going to be in the expo hall, the Yosemite room, at 345 today.

00:01:32.360 --> 00:01:37.320
So generally when I tell people that I work on the Arrow project in data science, they're

00:01:37.320 --> 00:01:42.320
like, oh, yeah, Arrow, that's awesome, I've heard of that, that's really cool.

00:01:42.320 --> 00:01:46.080
What is Arrow?

00:01:46.080 --> 00:01:51.599
And Arrow's a lot of things, and that kind of defies a simple explanation.

00:01:51.839 --> 00:01:58.320
One way that I like to frame it in terms particularly of what it means for the R community is that

00:01:58.320 --> 00:02:03.279
it's a foundation for the next generation of data frames.

00:02:03.279 --> 00:02:08.639
As anyone who's worked with bigger data in R has surely experienced, R is great and there's

00:02:08.639 --> 00:02:14.039
lots of powerful tools and really expressive ways of getting work done in R, but once you

00:02:14.039 --> 00:02:18.720
start getting data sets that are bigger than memory on your laptop, you have to do some

00:02:18.720 --> 00:02:21.800
special tricks to make it work.

00:02:21.800 --> 00:02:26.119
Often you have data sets where the data's split into multiple files, and you can work

00:02:26.119 --> 00:02:30.679
with this, but it's, again, it's not as natural.

00:02:30.679 --> 00:02:37.160
And many data sets have more complex data types than your base character, numeric factor

00:02:37.160 --> 00:02:39.600
and what have you.

00:02:39.600 --> 00:02:42.720
And of course, the more data we have, the more we want to throw all of our hardware

00:02:42.720 --> 00:02:43.720
at it.

00:02:43.720 --> 00:02:47.880
So it's very possible in R, but it's just not how R itself was designed.

00:02:47.880 --> 00:02:51.039
But we're in good company.

00:02:51.039 --> 00:02:59.559
These are not just problems of R. So Wes McKinney, who created the Pandas library for Python,

00:02:59.559 --> 00:03:09.160
ran into similar challenges there, and constraints on memory and on data types and whatnot.

00:03:09.160 --> 00:03:15.119
And so Wes and some others from the data community created the Apache Arrow project

00:03:15.119 --> 00:03:17.279
in 2016.

00:03:17.279 --> 00:03:22.600
You may have experienced the feather package, which came out of some of the initial explorations

00:03:22.600 --> 00:03:28.440
there, the prototype of the Arrow format, which makes it really easy to write data frames

00:03:28.440 --> 00:03:32.520
in R and read them in Pandas and vice versa.

00:03:32.520 --> 00:03:37.919
And the idea was to draw on all these lessons that we have from R and from Pandas and from

00:03:38.199 --> 00:03:43.720
the database community and build the next generation of data frame tools that were not

00:03:43.720 --> 00:03:48.119
tied to a specific language or implementation.

00:03:48.119 --> 00:03:51.880
So Arrow fundamentally is two classes of things.

00:03:51.880 --> 00:03:53.639
So first is the format.

00:03:53.639 --> 00:03:59.080
This is the specification of how bits are arranged in memory.

00:03:59.080 --> 00:04:02.639
It's columnar and it's independent of any language.

00:04:02.639 --> 00:04:08.559
And then there's implementations or bindings to other implementations in currently 11 languages.

00:04:08.559 --> 00:04:15.600
So the Python library and the R package, they both bind to the C++ library, which is where

00:04:15.600 --> 00:04:19.119
a lot of the development happens.

00:04:19.119 --> 00:04:25.119
So the R package has been on CRAN since August.

00:04:25.119 --> 00:04:27.200
We're about to do a new release.

00:04:27.200 --> 00:04:31.279
I'm hoping next week this will be up on CRAN, CRAN willing.

00:04:31.279 --> 00:04:36.200
And so some of the things I'm going to show you right now, I'm going to show a little

00:04:36.200 --> 00:04:39.000
code and talk about a few other features.

00:04:39.000 --> 00:04:41.239
They are not on CRAN right now.

00:04:41.239 --> 00:04:44.880
If you're interested in checking them out right now, not right now, but after I'm done

00:04:44.880 --> 00:04:50.119
talking, I guess, we build nightly versions of the packages that you can download.

00:04:50.119 --> 00:04:55.040
And there's a repository that you can point at and then do install packages against that.

00:04:55.040 --> 00:04:57.040
Don't worry, I'll show these links again.

00:04:57.040 --> 00:05:00.720
And again, they're also on the slides if you want to follow along.

00:05:00.720 --> 00:05:01.720
I mentioned code.

00:05:01.720 --> 00:05:02.720
So let me do this.

00:05:02.720 --> 00:05:05.720
Let me show you some code.

00:05:05.720 --> 00:05:10.160
I hope that's big enough.

00:05:10.160 --> 00:05:16.000
So one of the cool features that's coming out in the upcoming release of the R package

00:05:16.000 --> 00:05:17.000
is the datasets API.

00:05:17.000 --> 00:05:24.040
And this lets us point at a directory of files and then treat them as a single entity and

00:05:24.040 --> 00:05:26.720
then be able to do dplyr on them.

00:05:26.720 --> 00:05:30.600
So dplyr is not a dependency of the R package.

00:05:30.600 --> 00:05:32.399
It is an optional suggest dependency.

00:05:32.399 --> 00:05:37.279
So we have to load both of them if we want to use this feature.

00:05:37.279 --> 00:05:42.079
I've got, I'm going to look at, this is in the New York City taxi data.

00:05:42.079 --> 00:05:48.040
I've got about, I've got over ten years of data split into files per month.

00:05:48.040 --> 00:05:49.320
And you see what's in the directory here.

00:05:49.320 --> 00:05:53.640
I've got 125 files, so ten years and five months.

00:05:53.640 --> 00:05:59.720
And each directory is year, month, and then a parquet file with those in it.

00:05:59.720 --> 00:06:03.640
This is a lot of data, two billion rows.

00:06:03.640 --> 00:06:08.239
And so even with these compressed files, it's 37 gigabytes of data.

00:06:08.239 --> 00:06:13.600
So more than I can read into memory and hold the memory in this laptop.

00:06:13.600 --> 00:06:19.040
So the new version of the R package has this function open dataset that lets me just point

00:06:19.040 --> 00:06:20.519
at a directory.

00:06:20.519 --> 00:06:25.119
And I can also specify information about the path segments of those files that are

00:06:25.119 --> 00:06:26.119
in there.

00:06:26.119 --> 00:06:29.559
So in this case, the paths are year and month.

00:06:29.559 --> 00:06:33.519
And so that's useful data in our dataset.

00:06:33.519 --> 00:06:38.359
So when I scan all of the files and inspect the metadata of those parquet files and get

00:06:38.359 --> 00:06:43.839
the common schema of them, I also, you can see through here, I also get year and month

00:06:43.839 --> 00:06:46.880
added as essentially virtual columns there.

00:06:46.880 --> 00:06:48.880
And then I can use that in my queries.

00:06:48.880 --> 00:06:52.679
And importantly, I can filter against that, which means that I don't have to actually

00:06:52.679 --> 00:06:57.399
load all of those files in order to know that, for example, in this case, only files that

00:06:57.399 --> 00:07:02.119
are in that 2015 directory are going to have data for 2015.

00:07:02.119 --> 00:07:09.679
So I can run this fairly basic dplyr, do some filtering, selecting columns, and then do

00:07:09.679 --> 00:07:14.399
what is this, the median tip percentage on these rides.

00:07:14.399 --> 00:07:22.160
So I just scanned 2 billion rows in under four seconds, and here's my table.

00:07:22.160 --> 00:07:27.200
So let me jump back to slides.

00:07:27.200 --> 00:07:30.959
For those of you following along on the slides, this is actually a link here to that notebook

00:07:30.959 --> 00:07:31.959
that's also online.

00:07:31.959 --> 00:07:35.399
So you can check at that later.

00:07:35.399 --> 00:07:38.920
There's also a vignette in the new version of the package that walks through this and

00:07:38.920 --> 00:07:41.160
talks a little bit more about the feature.

00:07:41.160 --> 00:07:48.279
So with this datasets feature, we're able to point at a directory, and we can use parallel

00:07:48.279 --> 00:07:49.279
processing.

00:07:49.279 --> 00:07:50.600
I didn't have to tell it to do it.

00:07:50.600 --> 00:07:54.839
It's just taking advantage of all the CPU it can.

00:07:54.839 --> 00:07:57.359
And we're able to make efficient queries on this.

00:07:57.359 --> 00:08:00.880
And all the work is pushed down into these individual file chunks.

00:08:00.880 --> 00:08:05.920
So I don't need to be able to read the whole dataset into memory in order to query with

00:08:05.920 --> 00:08:06.920
it.

00:08:06.920 --> 00:08:09.160
There's a lot more we plan to do on this this year.

00:08:09.160 --> 00:08:12.799
So if this is interesting to you, stay tuned.

00:08:12.799 --> 00:08:18.519
More file formats, cloud storage, so that I can point at an S3 bucket, for example,

00:08:18.519 --> 00:08:22.320
and do the same type of operation just as smoothly.

00:08:22.320 --> 00:08:26.160
As well as faster aggregation in C++.

00:08:26.160 --> 00:08:28.239
I mentioned Parquet along the way.

00:08:28.239 --> 00:08:32.239
I believe the error package is the only one on CRAN now that lets you read and write Parquet

00:08:32.239 --> 00:08:33.239
files.

00:08:33.239 --> 00:08:39.880
If you're not familiar, Parquet is a common columnar binary file format used in a lot

00:08:39.880 --> 00:08:44.280
of data warehousing, ETL systems.

00:08:44.280 --> 00:08:48.719
And the really cool thing about it is that it supports multiple forms of compression

00:08:48.719 --> 00:08:49.719
and encoding.

00:08:49.719 --> 00:08:54.000
So you can get really small files that are also really fast to load and work with.

00:08:54.000 --> 00:08:57.520
We did some benchmarking of this a few months ago.

00:08:57.520 --> 00:09:02.359
And you can see that with this example file that we're looking at here, the read time

00:09:02.359 --> 00:09:07.320
is around in the same ballpark as all these other readers, but the file size is an order

00:09:07.320 --> 00:09:08.320
of magnitude smaller.

00:09:08.320 --> 00:09:10.559
So if you're not using Parquet, check it out.

00:09:10.559 --> 00:09:13.719
There's some cool stuff there.

00:09:13.719 --> 00:09:15.799
So I'm excited about this stuff.

00:09:15.799 --> 00:09:20.520
I think there's a lot of cool work in the new version of the error package coming out

00:09:20.520 --> 00:09:23.320
and that we're working on this year.

00:09:23.320 --> 00:09:26.039
But there are lots of ways to solve these problems.

00:09:26.039 --> 00:09:29.840
This is R, of course, so there's many solutions to every problem.

00:09:29.840 --> 00:09:35.239
And you could cobble together something from a number of different packages to solve the

00:09:35.239 --> 00:09:40.559
memory mapping or multiple files or point out a database or any number of solutions

00:09:40.559 --> 00:09:42.000
for this.

00:09:42.000 --> 00:09:43.640
And those are totally valid.

00:09:43.640 --> 00:09:47.599
And I'm certainly not going to try to convince you that you should use Arrow instead of doing

00:09:47.599 --> 00:09:48.599
that.

00:09:48.599 --> 00:09:54.719
What I want to talk about now, though, is why I think the Arrow project is unique and

00:09:54.719 --> 00:10:00.840
why it's worth following and considering whether it's appropriate for your projects.

00:10:00.840 --> 00:10:06.320
So the first thing is that, you know, I just demoed one thing here, but the Arrow, Apache

00:10:06.320 --> 00:10:09.239
Arrow project is much larger than that.

00:10:09.239 --> 00:10:11.200
And one measure of that is the number of contributors.

00:10:11.200 --> 00:10:16.440
We've got around 400 contributors, maybe more or less.

00:10:16.440 --> 00:10:18.479
And it's a steadily growing number.

00:10:18.479 --> 00:10:21.880
As you can see over the course of the history of the project here, you know, we're picking

00:10:21.880 --> 00:10:24.640
up about two new contributors every week.

00:10:24.640 --> 00:10:29.919
So this is a growing community, lots of people adding things to make the software better.

00:10:29.919 --> 00:10:30.919
Make the software better for you.

00:10:30.919 --> 00:10:35.599
And this, you know, in contrast with, you know, another project where maybe you've got

00:10:35.599 --> 00:10:41.640
one core maintainer or maybe two, you know, I think the sustainability as well of a project

00:10:41.640 --> 00:10:45.159
that has this type of foundation is really good.

00:10:45.159 --> 00:10:50.239
Second, as I mentioned, there's a lot more going on than just the features I demoed in

00:10:50.239 --> 00:10:54.559
R. These projects here are part of the Arrow broader

00:10:54.559 --> 00:10:55.559
project.

00:10:55.559 --> 00:10:58.960
And they don't currently have R bindings.

00:10:58.960 --> 00:11:00.919
Hopefully this year maybe we'll get some of those.

00:11:00.919 --> 00:11:05.559
One that's really cool, just to highlight one, is Flight, which is a client server framework

00:11:05.559 --> 00:11:10.640
for shipping columnar data around the network.

00:11:10.640 --> 00:11:14.760
And some folks have been using it and found it to be really fast and performant.

00:11:14.760 --> 00:11:19.440
So I'm really excited about seeing that in R as well.

00:11:19.440 --> 00:11:21.440
So there are lots of contributors.

00:11:21.440 --> 00:11:23.960
There are lots of projects that are also already using Arrow.

00:11:24.359 --> 00:11:29.200
And I don't say this to say, well, everyone else is doing it, so you should do it.

00:11:29.200 --> 00:11:34.919
But what it means is that there's a lot of other projects that have a vested interest

00:11:34.919 --> 00:11:38.739
in the growth and health of Arrow and in making it better.

00:11:38.739 --> 00:11:45.280
And also, if you're using some of these other projects, Arrow improves interoperability.

00:11:45.280 --> 00:11:48.280
So it is language independent.

00:11:48.280 --> 00:11:49.880
The format is language independent.

00:11:49.880 --> 00:11:57.200
And so it makes it easier for you to efficiently get data in and out of whatever database or

00:11:57.200 --> 00:11:58.960
system.

00:11:58.960 --> 00:12:04.440
One example of this in R is with the sparklyr package.

00:12:04.440 --> 00:12:14.599
Javier, who's talking next, he added features to sparklyr to take advantage of Arrow.

00:12:14.599 --> 00:12:17.960
Apache Spark database can emit Arrow data.

00:12:17.960 --> 00:12:23.280
And by adding support for reading that in R, just by loading the Arrow package now,

00:12:23.280 --> 00:12:26.599
you just get a 40x speedup when pulling data out of Spark.

00:12:26.599 --> 00:12:28.840
You don't have to do anything else.

00:12:28.840 --> 00:12:32.520
So I think there's a lot of opportunities for things like this.

00:12:32.520 --> 00:12:36.640
And like I said, if this is interesting to you, don't leave after I'm done talking.

00:12:36.640 --> 00:12:39.520
I know you're all here just for me.

00:12:39.520 --> 00:12:44.640
But Javier's going to talk a bit more about things in that ecosystem.

00:12:44.640 --> 00:12:50.359
I've said this a few times, but Arrow is language independent, language agnostic.

00:12:50.359 --> 00:12:54.479
And I think this has a number of nice properties for us in the R community.

00:12:54.479 --> 00:13:03.119
So unlike saving an R data file or something, if you write using Arrow, the data that you

00:13:03.119 --> 00:13:08.760
write is immediately readable by people in Python or in Java or Rust or Go or JavaScript

00:13:08.760 --> 00:13:10.979
or whatever.

00:13:10.979 --> 00:13:15.500
And so that really helps us with collaboration with people that, for whatever reason, aren't

00:13:15.500 --> 00:13:24.500
using R. And it also gives us an onramp to access all these other projects that use Arrow

00:13:24.500 --> 00:13:32.380
as their core representation, but that are not implemented in R.

00:13:32.380 --> 00:13:37.619
So one thing I'm hoping to get out this year at some point is support with Reticulate for

00:13:37.619 --> 00:13:39.179
Arrow data types.

00:13:39.179 --> 00:13:43.460
So this is just hypothetical code, because this hasn't been released yet.

00:13:43.460 --> 00:13:49.179
But for one example, NVIDIA has this project, the Rapids project, and they have a number

00:13:49.179 --> 00:13:58.140
of largely Python-based projects that use GPUs, GPU acceleration for machine learning.

00:13:58.140 --> 00:14:03.080
This one here in this example, CUDF, is a data frame library that uses GPUs.

00:14:03.080 --> 00:14:09.359
And so with Reticulate and Arrow, we should be able to just do our work using CUDF and

00:14:09.359 --> 00:14:16.599
then continue with our workflow in R as if it were in R. So again, not in the package.

00:14:16.599 --> 00:14:18.080
Don't run this code right now.

00:14:18.080 --> 00:14:19.880
But hopefully very soon.

00:14:19.880 --> 00:14:27.479
All right, so if this sounds interesting to you, I have some offers for you.

00:14:27.479 --> 00:14:31.080
First thing you can do to get involved is, of course, try out the package.

00:14:31.080 --> 00:14:34.880
I mentioned it's on CRAN.

00:14:34.880 --> 00:14:40.599
It's if you use Conda, we also have a Conda recipe.

00:14:40.599 --> 00:14:43.280
Here's the link again to our nightly repositories.

00:14:43.280 --> 00:14:48.679
We build binary packages for Mac and Windows as well as C++ binaries for a number of Linux

00:14:48.679 --> 00:14:53.760
distributions so that you can just point at our repository and download the latest development

00:14:53.760 --> 00:14:56.000
build that way.

00:14:56.000 --> 00:14:57.400
I mentioned Linux.

00:14:57.400 --> 00:15:02.880
If anyone here has tried installing Arrow previously on Linux and felt frustrated because

00:15:02.880 --> 00:15:08.039
you had to install system packages or whatever, I see some heads nodding, sorry.

00:15:08.039 --> 00:15:11.440
But as of the current release, this should no longer be an issue.

00:15:11.440 --> 00:15:16.919
The current release, the upcoming release will just work on Linux with no system dependencies

00:15:16.919 --> 00:15:17.919
required.

00:15:17.919 --> 00:15:21.320
And if you're really curious and want to learn more about that, we have a vignette that shows

00:15:21.320 --> 00:15:24.320
how that works.

00:15:24.320 --> 00:15:26.679
I mentioned our dev builds.

00:15:26.679 --> 00:15:33.000
I encourage you, if you want to use the latest Arrow, and again, we only do CRAN releases

00:15:33.000 --> 00:15:38.520
every three months or so, so if you want to check out what's going on in between those,

00:15:38.520 --> 00:15:43.359
which is often a lot, you should try our nightly builds.

00:15:43.359 --> 00:15:48.640
I would not recommend using install GitHub for Arrow just because of the C++ building

00:15:48.640 --> 00:15:49.840
stuff that it has to deal with.

00:15:49.840 --> 00:15:53.960
If you use our nightly builds, you won't have to worry with that.

00:15:53.960 --> 00:15:56.599
When you use Arrow, tell us about it.

00:15:56.599 --> 00:16:02.919
We are actively working hard to improve it, and there is zero chance we have anticipated

00:16:02.919 --> 00:16:07.080
every use case or weird data shape out there.

00:16:07.080 --> 00:16:09.239
I say weird, not in a judgmental way.

00:16:09.239 --> 00:16:12.679
There's lots of interesting data out there.

00:16:12.679 --> 00:16:16.320
And so tell us about it.

00:16:16.320 --> 00:16:19.280
We'd love to make it better.

00:16:19.280 --> 00:16:21.159
And of course, this is open source.

00:16:21.159 --> 00:16:26.080
This is community-supported software, and we can't do it except with contributors from

00:16:26.080 --> 00:16:27.919
users like you.

00:16:27.919 --> 00:16:33.679
So feel free to we will probably, if you write an issue, we will probably ask you if you

00:16:33.679 --> 00:16:36.239
are interested in submitting a pull request for it.

00:16:36.239 --> 00:16:37.960
Please do.

00:16:37.960 --> 00:16:44.960
And some of the projects can be highly technical, but other parts of it are much more accessible,

00:16:44.960 --> 00:16:50.960
and we'll do our best to provide on-ramps to help people who want to contribute.

00:16:50.960 --> 00:16:57.599
Documentation improvements, totally fair game, and I'm sure there's plenty of room for that.

00:16:57.599 --> 00:17:00.000
Finally, you can also sponsor Ursa Labs.

00:17:00.000 --> 00:17:07.239
So as I mentioned, we are a nonprofit organization funded by a number of companies, first among

00:17:07.239 --> 00:17:12.719
others by RStudio, as well as a number of other companies, and this lets us do some

00:17:12.719 --> 00:17:16.479
of the important things, kind of like what JJ was talking about in the keynote this morning,

00:17:16.479 --> 00:17:22.800
of having a dedicated team that is working to improve and foster the health of the community.

00:17:22.800 --> 00:17:26.680
And it lets us get off the ground some of these bigger projects and get a critical mass

00:17:26.680 --> 00:17:31.520
together to kick off the data sets or the query engine that we're working on this year

00:17:31.520 --> 00:17:32.520
and whatnot.

00:17:32.520 --> 00:17:39.160
It's really difficult to do in a pure volunteer open source project where people are contributing

00:17:39.160 --> 00:17:41.359
the time that they can.

00:17:41.359 --> 00:17:48.680
And also, we take seriously the open source community and our role within it as kind of

00:17:48.680 --> 00:17:53.040
maintainers and helping to make it easier for other people to contribute.

00:17:53.040 --> 00:17:56.939
So info at ursalabs.org if you're interested in this.

00:17:56.939 --> 00:18:02.880
And also, I don't know if this link works yet, but it looks like it might.

00:18:02.880 --> 00:18:06.920
We are hopefully coming up on GitHub sponsors, so you can just click there and give us money

00:18:06.920 --> 00:18:10.239
that way too.

00:18:10.239 --> 00:18:11.239
Thanks a lot.

00:18:11.239 --> 00:18:13.680
As I mentioned, I'll take some questions now.

00:18:13.680 --> 00:18:17.640
You can tweet at us or follow us at Apache Arrow, and that's me, at NPR.

00:18:17.640 --> 00:18:22.800
And we'll be in about an hour over in the Yosemite room after this session if you have

00:18:22.800 --> 00:18:23.800
any further questions.

00:18:23.800 --> 00:18:24.800
Thanks a lot.

00:18:24.800 --> 00:18:36.079
So we do have time for a few questions.

00:18:36.079 --> 00:18:40.959
If you haven't discovered it already, you can also submit questions on slido.com using

00:18:40.959 --> 00:18:45.280
the code HEXAGON that gives you a chance not only to submit questions, but vote on other

00:18:45.280 --> 00:18:47.239
people's questions as well.

00:18:47.239 --> 00:18:50.760
So does anybody have a question?

00:18:50.760 --> 00:18:51.760
There are a bunch on Slido.

00:18:51.760 --> 00:18:52.760
I was giving the room first.

00:18:52.760 --> 00:18:53.760
All right.

00:18:53.760 --> 00:18:55.640
Well, I'll go right to Slido then.

00:18:55.640 --> 00:18:57.839
So one of the first questions we...

00:18:57.839 --> 00:19:02.719
One of the most popular questions on Slido, the most popular question with 10 votes is

00:19:02.719 --> 00:19:05.880
data table is multi-threaded and very fast.

00:19:05.880 --> 00:19:10.560
What are the performance metrics between Arrow and data table?

00:19:11.160 --> 00:19:14.199
So it's not really a fair comparison.

00:19:14.199 --> 00:19:16.439
They have different goals.

00:19:16.439 --> 00:19:26.560
So what I just showed here of querying against a multi-file data set in Parquet, I haven't

00:19:26.560 --> 00:19:27.560
tried data table.

00:19:27.560 --> 00:19:30.239
I don't know if it supports multiple file data sets.

00:19:30.239 --> 00:19:33.040
If it does, that'd be interesting.

00:19:33.040 --> 00:19:39.560
Parquet reading, I think the goals of what we're doing in Arrow are slightly different

00:19:39.560 --> 00:19:41.560
from what data table's goals are.

00:19:41.560 --> 00:19:46.040
But one of the things that's very important to us is performance, obviously, and one of

00:19:46.040 --> 00:19:51.680
our goals for the year is to put up benchmarking information so that when we have questions

00:19:51.680 --> 00:19:56.959
like this, I can give a hard number instead of a not.

00:19:56.959 --> 00:20:01.040
So Javier, if you want to step up and start getting ready, we'll do another question from

00:20:01.040 --> 00:20:02.040
the audience.

00:20:02.040 --> 00:20:09.040
I just wanted to say that I was testing that the other day, and on some very large but

00:20:09.040 --> 00:20:15.160
very simply structured data sets, Arrow was reading and writing about twice as fast.

00:20:15.160 --> 00:20:16.160
Cool.

00:20:16.160 --> 00:20:20.079
But on relatively small data sets, data table was quite a bit faster.

00:20:20.079 --> 00:20:21.079
All right.

00:20:21.079 --> 00:20:22.640
Good to know.

00:20:22.640 --> 00:20:24.680
Thank you.

00:20:24.680 --> 00:20:27.760
Another popular question is, is Feather dead?

00:20:27.760 --> 00:20:31.479
And there was a related question around whether Feather was appropriate for long-term storage

00:20:31.479 --> 00:20:32.479
or not.

00:20:32.479 --> 00:20:34.160
Excellent questions.

00:20:34.160 --> 00:20:44.160
So we view Feather as kind of like the first version of the Arrow format standard.

00:20:44.160 --> 00:20:47.719
It's very effective, but it also has a number of limitations in terms of the data types

00:20:47.719 --> 00:20:49.800
it supports.

00:20:49.800 --> 00:20:56.880
So what we're looking to do is to have kind of a 2.0 version of Feather that is essentially

00:20:56.880 --> 00:21:00.439
the Arrow format going forward.

00:21:00.439 --> 00:21:04.719
There are a number of things that we're working on this year around addressing that sort of

00:21:04.719 --> 00:21:09.439
stability of the Arrow format and its long-term applications.

00:21:09.439 --> 00:21:14.760
We've got our 1.0 release coming up, hopefully in the coming months.

00:21:14.760 --> 00:21:15.760
Right, Wes?

00:21:15.760 --> 00:21:16.760
It's not dead.

00:21:16.760 --> 00:21:17.760
Yeah.

00:21:17.760 --> 00:21:25.000
And no, not at all dead, and I think there will be an evolution going forward, but it's

00:21:25.000 --> 00:21:26.000
not dead.

00:21:26.000 --> 00:21:27.000
Excellent.

00:21:27.000 --> 00:21:28.000
Thank you.

00:21:28.000 --> 00:21:29.000
Another round of applause for Neil, please.

00:21:29.000 --> 00:21:30.000
Thank you.

00:21:30.000 --> 00:21:31.000
Thank you.

00:21:31.000 --> 00:21:31.000


